<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> The poem uses the name "Lucifer" only three times, as against 72 mentions of "Satan"</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> The <a href="/wiki/Romanian_language" title="Romanian language">Romanian</a> word <i><a href="/wiki/Luceaf%C4%83r" title="Luceafăr">Luceafăr</a></i>, though derived from the Latin word, is applied also to the evening appearance of Venus and, in addition, to the fixed stars <a href="/wiki/Aldebaran" title="Aldebaran">Aldebaran</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sirius" title="Sirius">Sirius</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Vega" title="Vega">Vega</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> The Greek word Ἑωσφόρος (Heosphoros), meaning "Dawn-Bringer", which is also used as a name for the Morning Star, is the name used in the Greek Translation of the Old Testament. <a href="/wiki/Eos" title="Eos">Eos</a> was the Greek Goddess of Dawn.</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> The word has taken the form "<a href="/wiki/Luceaf%C4%83r" title="Luceafăr">Luceafăr</a>" in modern <a href="/wiki/Romanian_language" title="Romanian language">Romanian</a>; and "Luzbel" in Spanish, "Lusbel" in Portuguese, may be a folk evolution of Latin <i>lucĭfer</i> (<i>Luz</i> in the <i>Diccionario Crítico Etimológico Castellano e Hispánico</i>, volume III, <a href="/wiki/Joan_Corominas" title="Joan Corominas" class="mw-redirect">Joan Corominas</a>, José A. Pascual, 1989, Editorial Gredos, <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/8424913655" class="internal">ISBN 84-249-1365-5</a>).</li>
