<li id="cite_note-Jewish-12">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Jewish_12-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Jewish_12-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Jewish_12-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=612&amp;letter=L" class="external text" title="http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=612&amp;letter=L" rel="nofollow">Jewish Encyclopedia: article <i>Lucifer</i></a></li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> "Verses 12-15 seem to be based on a <a href="/wiki/Phoenicia" title="Phoenicia">Phoenician</a> model. At all events, they display several points of contact with the Ras-Shamra poems: Daystar and Dawn were two divinities; the "mount of Assembly" was where the gods used to meet, like <a href="/wiki/Mount_Olympus" title="Mount Olympus">Mount Olympus</a> in <a href="/wiki/Greek_mythology" title="Greek mythology">Greek mythology</a>. The Fathers identified the fall of the Morning Star (Vulgate, <i>Lucifer</i>) with that of the prince of the demons" (note in the <a href="/wiki/New_Jerusalem_Bible" title="New Jerusalem Bible">New Jerusalem Bible</a>).</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> The <a href="/wiki/Septuagint" title="Septuagint">Septuagint</a> Greek translation of the phrase uses the same interpretation of "son of dawn": ὁ ἑωσφόρος ὁ πρωὶ ἀνατέλλων.</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> Verses 29:4, 31:4 of the longer recension manuscript R</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> Your heart is proud and you have said, "I am a god; I sit in the seat of the gods, in the heart of the seas" … By your great wisdom in trade you have increased your wealth, and your heart has become proud in your wealth (verses 2 and 5)</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> With an anointed cherub as guardian I placed you; you were on the holy mountain of God; you walked among the stones of fire. You were blameless in your ways from the day that you were created, until iniquity was found in you. In the abundance of your trade you were filled with violence, and you sinned; so I cast you as a profane thing from the mountain of God, and the guardian cherub drove you out from among the stones of fire (verses 14-16).</li>
